---
import DefaultLayout from '@snaix/docs-theme/layouts/DefaultLayout.astro';
import { BlockReveal } from '@snaix/docs-theme';
---
<DefaultLayout title="snaix · manifesto">
  <div class="page about">
    <nav class="ds-nav">
      <a href="/" class="ds-nav-home">← snaix.homes</a>
      <div class="ds-nav-links">
        <a href="/design-system/">design language</a>
        <a href="#stance">stance</a>
      </div>
    </nav>

    <section class="manifesto-hero">
      <div class="manifesto-shapes" aria-hidden="true">
        <div class="mh-red" />
        <div class="mh-yellow" />
        <div class="mh-blue" />
      </div>
      <div class="t-small" style="color: var(--red); position: relative; z-index: 2;">§ manifesto</div>
      <h1 class="manifesto-title lower">
        <BlockReveal client:visible>small tools,</BlockReveal><br />
        <BlockReveal client:visible delay={300} color="var(--red)">readable,</BlockReveal><br />
        <BlockReveal client:visible delay={600} color="var(--blue)">in your hands.</BlockReveal>
      </h1>
    </section>

    <section class="manifesto-body">
      <div class="mb-side">
        <div>§ 01 · position</div>
        <div>no telemetry</div>
        <div>no account</div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          snaix is where i put the tools i build for myself and decide are
          worth sharing. cli, tui, macos-native. apache-2.0 or mit,
          permissively. written to be read end-to-end, not black-boxed
          behind sdks.
        </p>
        <p>
          four principles run through every tool here. <span class="highlight">
          software you can read. tools that don't phone home. interfaces
          that respect your hands. defaults that are the right answer.</span>
        </p>
        <p>
          bcmr treats transfers as a promise you keep — every byte hashed on
          both ends, or the transfer didn't succeed. pikpaktui puts a cloud
          drive under 26 keyboard shortcuts. iconchanger swaps macos icons
          with a live dock preview. claudit reads your <code>~/.claude</code>
          logs so you can see what you actually spent. no cloud for any of
          them. no account. no phone-home.
        </p>
        <p>
          every tool on this site is open source. nothing is served from an
          api you can't inspect. every release is built from a commit you
          can check out, diff, and compile. the whole point is that you can
          read the code and know exactly what your machine is doing to your
          files, your keystrokes, your logs.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="credits" id="stance">
      <div style="margin-bottom: 20px;">
        <div class="t-small" style="color: var(--red);">§ stance</div>
        <h2 class="t-h1 lower" style="margin-top: 8px;">open source.<br />zero telemetry.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="credits-grid">
        <div class="credit">
          <div class="credit-role">license</div>
          <div class="credit-name">mit · apache-2.0</div>
          <div class="credit-loc">no strings attached</div>
        </div>
        <div class="credit">
          <div class="credit-role">telemetry</div>
          <div class="credit-name">none</div>
          <div class="credit-loc">no account · no ping</div>
        </div>
        <div class="credit">
          <div class="credit-role">source</div>
          <div class="credit-name">readable</div>
          <div class="credit-loc">one afternoon, end-to-end</div>
        </div>
        <div class="credit">
          <div class="credit-role">built with</div>
          <div class="credit-name">rust · swift · astro</div>
          <div class="credit-loc">native where it matters</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</DefaultLayout>

<style>
  .about { max-width: 1240px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 32px 80px; }
</style>
